      <h2>What Is an Industrial Static Eliminator?</h2>
      <p>
        An <strong>industrial static eliminator</strong> is a device that generates ions to neutralize static charge on production materials. It is a core component of any industrial ESD control program. Grounding equipment works only on conductive objects. Static eliminators work on insulators — films, panels, PCBs, and plastics. They flood the area with balanced positive and negative ions. The ions attach to the charged surface and cancel the charge.
      </p>
      <p>
        Industrial static eliminators come in several form factors. Bar-type ionizers mount above conveyors. Fan-based ion blowers cover workstations. Rod-type units integrate directly into machines. Each form factor suits different production layouts and line speeds.
      </p>

      <h3>Why Static Charge Is a Problem in Manufacturing</h3>
      <p>
        Static charge builds on any material that moves, separates, or contacts another surface. This is the triboelectric effect. When two materials contact and separate, electrons transfer from one to the other. One surface becomes negatively charged. The other becomes positively charged. The result is a charged material that attracts dust, causes ESD events, and disrupts production processes.
      </p>
      <p>
        At production line speeds, charge builds fast. A polarizer film moving on a conveyor can reach high voltage levels — several thousand volts — within seconds. At high voltage, the charged material pulls airborne particles from the air. It also creates discharge events that damage sensitive electronic components.
      </p>
      <p>
        The main production problems caused by uncontrolled static charge are:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>ESD damage to components</strong> — discharge events damage semiconductor junctions, gate oxides, and metallization. These failures are invisible but permanent.</li>
        <li><strong>Particle adhesion</strong> — negatively charged surfaces attract positively charged dust particles. Particles stick before cleaning steps can remove them, causing optical defects and surface failures.</li>
        <li><strong>Process jams</strong> — static cling between sheets, webs, or film layers causes misfeeds in printing and converting equipment.</li>
        <li><strong>Coating failures</strong> — high surface charge disrupts ink and coating adhesion on plastic and film substrates.</li>
        <li><strong>Operator shocks</strong> — charged materials discharge through operators, causing discomfort and safety concerns.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Industrial Static Eliminator Applications by Industry</h3>

      <h4>Electronics and PCB Manufacturing</h4>
      <p>
        PCB manufacturing requires ESD control at every handling point. Ionizing bars at conveyor infeed and outfeed positions neutralize charge on boards before screen printing, component placement, and inspection. ESD control at these stages protects sensitive components and reduces yield loss.
      </p>
      <p>
        For SMT assembly lines, inline ionizers match conveyor speed. They provide continuous static control without stopping the line. DGSDK's <a href="/products/static-eliminator/st-g-series">ST-G series</a> intelligent ionizing bars include balance monitoring and alarm output for uninterrupted ESD control on production lines.
      </p>

      <h4>Display and Optical Film Manufacturing</h4>
      <p>
        Display manufacturing has some of the most demanding ESD control requirements in industry. Polarizer films, diffusion sheets, and glass panels are large, insulating, and moved at conveyor speeds. A 500mm-wide polarizer moving at 20 m/min reaches high voltage levels within a few meters of travel.
      </p>
      <p>
        At these voltage levels, the charged material attracts particles before cleaning. ESD events during handling damage display driver ICs and thin-film transistor arrays. Full-width ionizing bars across the conveyor width are the standard ESD control solution for display lines. DGSDK supplies bar-length static eliminators for these applications.
      </p>

      <h4>Printing and Converting</h4>
      <p>
        Printing presses and web converting lines generate charge from high-speed material movement through rollers and nip points. Static-related problems in these lines include sheet misfeeds, web breaks, operator shocks, and ink jet deflection.
      </p>
      <p>
        Static eliminators for printing mount near the point of charge generation — at rollers, nip points, and delivery stacks. Fast-response ionizers work best at these positions. The closer the ionizer is to the charged material, the faster it neutralizes the charge.
      </p>

      <h4>Plastics and Injection Molding</h4>
      <p>
        Plastic parts leave the mold carrying high surface charge. The charged material immediately attracts airborne dust. This contamination happens before inspection or packaging, causing visible surface defects. Ion blowers directed at parts as they exit the mold remove surface charge before dust can settle.
      </p>
      <p>
        For plastic film extrusion lines, bar-type ionizers at the die and winding station neutralize charge. Without ESD control, inter-layer cling in wound rolls and particle adhesion on optical films are common problems.
      </p>

      <h4>Cleanroom and Optical Component Manufacturing</h4>
      <p>
        Cleanroom static eliminators have specific requirements. Low ozone output protects air quality. Low particle generation from the ionizer itself protects surfaces. Compatibility with laminar airflow is essential.
      </p>
      <p>
        DC-type ionizing bars are preferred in cleanrooms. They produce less ozone than AC models and deliver more stable ion output. In optical component manufacturing — lenses, filters, and coated glass — even tiny particles cause coating failures. Static eliminators before each coating and inspection station keep surfaces clean between process steps.
      </p>

      <h3>How to Select an Industrial Static Eliminator</h3>
      <p>
        Selecting the right static eliminator for an application involves several key criteria:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Application type</strong> — conveyor lines need ionizing bars; workstations need ion blowers; machine enclosures need compact rod-type units.</li>
        <li><strong>Coverage width</strong> — the ionizing bar must span the full width of the charged material. Standard bar lengths range from 150mm to over 2,000mm.</li>
        <li><strong>Working distance</strong> — the gap between the ionizer and the charged material affects neutralization speed. Shorter working distances improve performance at high line speeds.</li>
        <li><strong>Line speed</strong> — fast lines need pulse DC ionizers with short response times. Slow or intermittent lines can use AC ionizers.</li>
        <li><strong>Environment</strong> — cleanroom use requires low-ozone DC models. Harsh or corrosive environments require sealed construction.</li>
        <li><strong>Monitoring</strong> — production-critical lines benefit from ionizers with built-in balance monitoring and alarm output for continuous ESD control verification.</li>
      </ul>

